Caspase Substrate Analysis

Ryan Knight

24/01/2021

1 Introduction

Caspases (cysteine aspartases), are a family of proteases that carry out essential roles in forms of programmed cell death.

Cellular stress and infection promote the assembly of inflammasome complexes, leading to the activation of inflammatory caspases. Activation of these inflammatory caspases, Caspase-1, Caspase-4 and Caspase-5 in humans, and Caspase-1 and Caspase-11 in mice, induces a morphologically distinct form of programmed cell death known as pyroptosis. When undergoing pyroptosis, cells rupture and release their contents, including pro-inflammatory cytokines and danger signals to both prevent intracellular pathogen replication and induce an immune response.

Despite their namesake, there exists substantive evidence that caspases do not exclusively cleave substrates at aspartate residues but have a propensity to act at a variety of other amino acid residues (Seaman et al. 2016), most notably glutamate, possessing similar acidic properties to aspartate.

For our previous work (unpublished data), we compiled a database of inflammatory caspase substrates. As appreciation is developing for the more nuanced nature of caspase cleavage site consensus sequences, this report aims to provide a reproducible analysis and visualisation of features of caspase cleavage sites.

2 Methods and Results

2.1 Visualisation of consensus sequence characteristics

The acquired database of inflammatory caspase substrates was tidied into an amenable format, and cleavage site consensus interpreted with ggseqlogo (Wagih 2017).

Amino acids were categorised by chemical properties- acidity/basicity, hydrophobicity/polarity, and visualised in four plots: all 154 inflammatory caspase substrates, 113 human Caspase-1 substrates, 30 murine Caspase-1 substrates and 8 human Caspase-4 substrates. Human Caspase-5 and murine Caspase-11 substrate consensus is not presented as few substrates have been recorded.

Figure 2.1: Visualisation of inflammatory Caspase cleavage sites consensus categorised by chemistry, and position 10-11 represents the site of cleavage. A: all Caspases (154 sites), B: Caspase-4 (8), C: human Caspase-1 (113), D: murine Caspase-1 (30).

Visualisations shown in Figure 2.1 demonstrate the lack of an apparent pattern in the consensus sequence, with the exception of an aspartate (D), or minorly glutamate (E), residue at the cleavage site at position 10.

It should be noted that the studies comprising this data set did observe some sites with other residues in this position, though they were deliberately excluded from the compiled data set as there is insufficient experimental evidence for cleavage at sites other than D and E. These observations could reasonably be due to experimental artefacts such as contamination with other proteases such as cathepsins.

Regardless, the observed results diverge greatly from the traditional dogma of DEVD cleavage sites for caspases that would lie at P7-P10 in Figure 2.1. Site chemistry also follows no discernible pattern, nor does a hydrophobicity scale of human Caspase-1 sites, the largest sample in the data set (Figure 2.2).

Figure 2.2: Representation of consensus accross 113 human Caspase-1 cleavage sites, coloured by relative hydrophobicity.

Rationally, there is a factor other than local primary sequence chemistry explaining the identification of cleavage sites by inflammatory caspases, such as higher-order protein structure of post-translational modification.

Visualisation of the consistency of substrate P4-P1 residues between model species (Figure 2.3) shows a high degree of conservation.

This suggests that the amino acid residues surrounding the cleavage site are important, despite the general inconsistency of their chemistry (Figure 2.1). Post-translational modifications are therefore an ideal candidate for investigation.

Figure 2.3: Simple representation of assessment of substrate P4-P1 conservation in model organsisms (Ape = P. troglodytes, Human = H. sapiens, Mouse = M. musculus, Zebrafish = D. rerio. A) 113 sites cleaved by human Caspase-1. B) 30 sites cleaved by murine Caspase-1.

2.2 Phosphate site analysis

Position 10 is the cleavage site (D/E). B)

Some proteomic analysis performed on apopototic caspases has suggested that phosphorylation at cleavage sites can impact the efficiency of proteolysis (Dix et al. 2012). It is possible that post-translational phosphorylation, which occurs at Serine (S), Threonine, (T) and Tyrosine (Y) residues.

Data was tidied into an amenable format for analysis with a modified fork of phosphate site prediction model, DeepPhos which was assesed to be capable of identification of previously unknown phosphate sites (Luo et al. 2019). 123 human inflammatory Caspase substrates were processed using the DeepPhos prediction model against a threshold score of 0.5 (measured between 0 and 1). Results were categorised by position in the sequence and represented in Figure 2.4.

Position 10 represents the cleavage site (D/E), explaining the lack of any predicted phosphorylation sites at this position. An unexpectedly high number proportion of positions had prevalent phosphorylation, at a mean prevalence of 0.143 (n = 123, s.d. 0.051), the greatest of which was position 11 with a predicted phosphorylation frequency of 0.293.

Figure 2.4: Representations of phosphorylation prediction results (score threshold 0.5) amongst a sample of 123 human inflammatory Caspase substrates. A) Plot of prevelance of possible phosphorylated residues within the data set. B) Evaluation of the strength of mean phosphate prediction scores for each position. Error bars show the standard error of the mean.

Figure 2.4 also contains a representation of relative strengths of potential phosphorylation sites between positions. Standard errors of the mean were calculated and depicted in error bars as an indication of the accuracy of computation of the mean. Overlapping standard error bars suggest that differences in strength between sites is either not, or minimally, statistically significant (though statistical testing beyond visualization would be required to evaluate this).

It appears that out of the phosphate site predictions above quality threshold no position has a strong or weak phosphorylation tendency compared to the other positions (with the understandable exception of the cleavage point), which was unexpected. However, this visualisation did show that potential phosphorylation sites have reasonably high prediction scores compared to the commonly applied quality threshold of 0.5.
